{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_66","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc \"pwd && cat > REPORT.md << 'EOF'\n# How Does the Model Count in French?\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\nWe tested whether modern LLMs represent French counting patterns, especially the irregular \"'`70-99` range (`soixante-dix`, `quatre-vingt-dix` family), in a measurable and mappable way.\n\nKey finding: for numeral transduction tasks, models were near-perfect and did **not** degrade on `70-99`; the strongest band effect appeared in a controlled *pattern classification* probe, where irregular-range items were easier than regular-range items under our label schema.\n\nPractical implication: current strong LLMs can reliably map French numeral words and digits in low-temperature settings, but probe design strongly affects conclusions about “representation difficulty.”\n\n## 2. Goal\n### Hypothesis\nLarge language models represent and process French counting in a way that can be mapped and analyzed, despite its counterintuitive structure.\n\n### Why this matters\nFrench numeric forms are compositionally transparent but atypical. Reliable handling affects multilingual education, translation, and safety-critical numeric communication.\n\n### Problem solved\nWe provide a reproducible probe pipeline to quantify where models succeed/fail in French counting and how those failures distribute by number band.\n\n## 3. Data Construction\n### Dataset Description\n- Synthetic French numeral probe set (`0-199`) generated by canonical rules in [src/french_numerals.py](/workspaces/french-model-counting-9f9d-codex/src/french_numerals.py).\n- MGSM French benchmark subset from `datasets/mgsm/mgsm_fr.tsv`.\n\n### Example Samples\n- Synthetic: `71 -> soixante et onze`, `95 -> quatre-vingt-quinze`, `199 -> cent quatre-vingt-dix-neuf`.\n- MGSM examples are in `results/data_samples.json`.\n\n### Data Quality\nFrom `results/data_profile.json`:\n- MGSM rows: 250\n- Missing MGSM question: 0.0%\n- Missing MGSM answer: 1.6%\n- Duplicate MGSM questions: 0\n- Synthetic rows: 200\n- Synthetic duplicates: 0\n\n### Preprocessing Steps\n1. Generated canonical French numeral strings for `0-199`.\n2. Normalized predicted text (hyphen/spacing variants, lowercasing).\n3. Parsed integer outputs with regex for inverse tasks.\n4. Banded numbers into `0-69`, `70-99`, `100-199`.\n\n### Train/Val/Test Splits\n- No training in this study (inference-only evaluation).\n- Synthetic probes: full-coverage test set (`0-199`).\n- MGSM: benchmark subset used as test-style evaluation.\n\n## 4. Experiment Description\n### Methodology\n#### High-Level Approach\nBlack-box API probing with deterministic generation (`temperature=0`) across tasks:\n- `digit_to_word`\n- `word_to_digit`\n- `pattern_classification`\n- `mgsm_fr`\n\n#### Why this method\nIt directly measures functional representation quality without simulating model behavior.\n\n### Implementation Details\n#### Tools and Libraries\n- Python 3.12.8\n- openai 2.26.0\n- pandas 3.0.1\n- numpy 2.4.2\n- scipy 1.17.1\n- statsmodels 0.14.6\n- matplotlib 3.10.8\n- seaborn 0.13.2\n\n#### Models\n- `gpt-4.1`\n- `gpt-4.1-mini`\n\n#### Hyperparameters\n| Parameter | Value | Selection Method |\n|-----------|-------|------------------|\n| temperature | 0 | deterministic eval default |\n| max_output_tokens | 180 | sufficient for short responses |\n| seed | 42 | reproducibility |\n\n### Experimental Protocol\n#### Reproducibility Information\n- Hardware: 2 x NVIDIA RTX 3090 (24GB each)\n- Raw outputs: `results/raw/raw_outputs_20260308_214204.jsonl`\n- Analyzed table: `results/raw/raw_outputs_20260308_214204_partial.csv`\n- Note: a very long run was interrupted; analyzed data contains full `gpt-4.1` (direct/reasoned), full `gpt-4.1-mini` direct, and partial `gpt-4.1-mini` reasoned.\n\n#### Evaluation Metrics\n- Accuracy (exact/normalized)\n- Band-wise risk difference (`70-99` vs regular bands)\n- Two-proportion z-tests + FDR correction\n- Logistic regression (`correct ~ irregular + model + condition + task`)\n\n### Raw Results\n#### Aggregate\n- Total analyzed rows: 1,935\n- Overall accuracy: 0.8351\n- API error rows: 0\n\n#### Core task results (selected)\n| Model | Condition | Task | 0-69 | 70-99 | 100-199 |\n|---|---|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| gpt-4.1 | direct | digit_to_word | 0.9857 | 1.0000 | 1.0000 |\n| gpt-4.1 | reasoned | digit_to_word | 0.9857 | 1.0000 | 1.0000 |\n| gpt-4.1-mini | direct | digit_to_word | 0.9714 | 0.9667 | 1.0000 |\n| gpt-4.1 | direct | word_to_digit | 1.0000 | 1.0000 | 1.0000 |\n| gpt-4.1 | reasoned | word_to_digit | 1.0000 | 1.0000 | 1.0000 |\n| gpt-4.1-mini | direct | word_to_digit | 1.0000 | 1.0000 | 1.0000 |\n\n#### MGSM-FR\n| Model | Condition | Accuracy |\n|---|---|---:|\n| gpt-4.1 | direct | 0.4875 |\n| gpt-4.1 | reasoned | 0.5750 |\n\n### Output Locations\n- Metrics JSON: `results/metrics.json`\n- Summary CSV: `results/summary_metrics.csv`\n- Significance tests: `results/band_significance_tests.csv`\n- Plots:\n  - `results/accuracy_by_band.png`\n  - `results/condition_effect_core_tasks.png`\n  - `results/per_number_accuracy_digit_to_word.png`\n\n## 5. Result Analysis\n### Key Findings\n1. `digit_to_word` and `word_to_digit` performance is extremely high across bands; no strong irregular-band penalty in this setup.\n2. `word_to_digit` is ceiling-level (100%) in all complete model/condition runs.\n3. `pattern_classification` shows large, significant band differences (FDR-corrected p < 0.001) favoring irregular-band items.\n4. For MGSM-FR, reasoning prompt improved `gpt-4.1` from 48.8% to 57.5%.\n\n### Hypothesis Testing\n- The broad hypothesis (“representation can be mapped and analyzed”) is supported.\n- The specific expectation of degraded `70-99` transduction is **not** supported in this deterministic setup.\n\nSelected statistical results:\n- `gpt-4.1 direct digit_to_word`: risk diff = +0.0059, p = 0.6737 (ns)\n- `gpt-4.1-mini direct digit_to_word`: risk diff = -0.0216, p = 0.3702 (ns)\n- `pattern_classification` effects significant after FDR for all complete runs\n\nLogistic model (`n=1775`) highlights:\n- Irregular-band coefficient positive and significant (p ≈ 1.19e-9)\n- Condition effect (reasoned vs direct) not significant in pooled core probes (p ≈ 0.83)\n\n### Error Analysis\nRepresentative transduction failure:\n- `71`: gold `soixante et onze`, prediction `soixante-et-onze` (orthographic variant)\n\nMost observed “errors” are formatting/variant issues rather than numeric misunderstanding.\n\n### Limitations\n- Final block (`gpt-4.1-mini` reasoned) was partial due runtime constraints.\n- Pattern-classification probe may privilege irregular forms by label design.\n- No token-level logprob/mechanistic activation analysis in this run.\n\n## 6. Conclusions\nThe study successfully maps French counting behavior for strong API LLMs with reproducible probes and statistics. In this configuration, models do not show a clear irregular-range weakness for direct numeral transduction; they are nearly perfect. The strongest observable structure appears in classification-style probes and in broader math reasoning (MGSM), where prompting has larger impact than numeral transduction itself.\n\nConfidence is moderate-high for the completed conditions and moderate overall due one incomplete model-condition block.\n\n## 7. Next Steps\n1. Complete the missing `gpt-4.1-mini reasoned` block for full factorial balance.\n2. Add stricter canonicalization (accept historical hyphenation reform variants explicitly).\n3. Add token-level and mechanistic probes (attention/head-level) on an open model.\n4. Expand to Belgium/Swiss French numeral variants (`septante`, `nonante`) as OOD tests.\n\n## References\n- `literature_review.md`\n- `resources.md`\n- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_language#Numerals\n- Wallace et al. (2019), Geva et al. (2020), Shi et al. (2022), Yu & Ananiadou (2024), and others listed in `literature_review.md`.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
